President Joseph R. Biden Jr. has proclaimed October 3-9, 2021, as Fire Prevention Week in the United States. In his proclamation, he acknowledges the bravery and sacrifice of firefighters and first responders who protect citizens daily. President Biden emphasizes the importance of fire safety and preparedness, urging Americans to educate themselves on fire prevention and take necessary precautions to prevent fires. He highlights the devastating impact of wildfires, which have already burned millions of acres of land and caused significant damage to homes, communities, and the economy. The President emphasizes that these wildfires are a result of climate change and calls for bold action to address this threat. The administration has proposed investing billions of dollars in wildfire preparedness, resilience, and response, which not only saves lives and homes but also creates new jobs and protects industries. President Biden's administration is committed to supporting wildland firefighters by ensuring they have adequate training, equipment, and pay. He encourages Americans to install and maintain smoke alarms in their homes and participate in fire safety programs and activities. The proclamation also mentions that on October 3, the flag of the United States will be flown at half-staff to honor the National Fallen Firefighters Memorial Service. President Biden calls on all Americans to renew their efforts to prevent fires and their tragic consequences.